  "text": "Pod eviction on memory pressure in Kubernetes is handled by the kubelet's eviction manager. The memory pressure thresholds are defined in platform-specific files: defaults_linux.go sets a hard eviction threshold of 100Mi for 'memory.available', while defaults_windows.go sets 500Mi. These thresholds are defined as strings in the DefaultEvictionHard map and parsed into Threshold objects using ParseThresholdConfig in helpers.go.\n\nThe signal types for memory pressure are defined in api/types.go as SignalMemoryAvailable and SignalAllocatableMemoryAvailable, which map to the NodeMemoryPressure condition through the signalToNodeCondition map in helpers.go.\n\nThe eviction manager's decision logic is implemented in eviction_manager.go. The synchronize() method is the main control loop that:\n\n1. Makes observations of available memory using makeSignalObservations() in helpers.go, which calls makeMemoryAvailableSignalObservation() from platform-specific files (helpers_others.go for Linux) to get current memory stats from the node summary.\n\n2. Evaluates thresholds using thresholdsMet() in helpers.go, which compares observed available memory against configured threshold values.\n\n3. Checks grace periods using thresholdsMetGracePeriod() to allow temporary threshold breaches before triggering eviction.\n\n4. Ranks pods for eviction using rankMemoryPressure() in helpers.go, which sorts pods based on memory usage exceeding requests and overall memory consumption.\n\n5. Invokes evictPod() to terminate selected pods with the eviction reason 'Evicted'.\n\nThe ranking function for memory signals is registered in buildSignalToRankFunc() in helpers.go, which maps both SignalMemoryAvailable and SignalAllocatableMemoryAvailable to the rankMemoryPressure function. Memory signals are given highest eviction priority through the byEvictionPriority comparison logic."
}

